            {
              "id": "01262f04-ac12-3e23-864f-10c8ecdd2bab",
              "name": "Detected Private Key Hardcoding Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoding private keys in the source code is a serious security vulnerability. It exposes the private key to anyone who has access to the source code, which can lead to unauthorized access, data breaches, and other security issues. This vulnerability is especially dangerous in open-source projects where the source code is publicly accessible.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\n- Never hardcode sensitive information, such as private keys, in the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information.\n- Use secure methods to store and retrieve sensitive information. For example, use a secure vault service or a secure, encrypted database.\n- Regularly rotate and change private keys to limit the potential damage if a key is compromised.\n- Use code scanning tools to detect hardcoded private keys in the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the private key in the source code, you should store it in an environment variable. Here is an example of how to do this in Python:\n\n```python\nimport os\n\nprivate_key = os.getenv('PRIVATE_KEY')\n```\n\nIn this example, `PRIVATE_KEY` is an environment variable that contains the private key. You can set this environment variable in your operating system, or in the configuration of your application server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
