            {
              "id": "64f4d57f-eb97-3ba9-ade5-c9dd5bc2d8ba",
              "name": "Potential Code Injection Vulnerability Detected through exec() Usage",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Python, the `exec()` function is used to execute dynamically created program, which can be a string or object code. If this function is used in a way that allows an attacker to manipulate the input, it can lead to a code injection vulnerability. This is because the attacker can inject malicious code, which will be executed by the program.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `exec(f.read(), _globals)`, the `exec()` function is used to execute the content of a file. If an attacker can control the content of this file, they can execute arbitrary Python code with the same privileges as the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `exec()` function with user-supplied input. If dynamic code execution is necessary, consider using safer alternatives like built-in Python functions or modules that can evaluate expressions or parse the specific language syntax you need.\n\nIf you must use `exec()`, make sure to validate and sanitize the input. You can use allow-lists, deny-lists, or regular expressions to ensure that the input only contains safe characters. Also, limit the scope of `exec()` by not passing the global context.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of executing the content of the file directly, you should read the content, validate it, and then process it in a safe way. Here is an example of how you can do this:\n\n```python\nwith open('file.txt', 'r') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\n# Validate the content here...\n\n# If the content is valid, then process it\nresult = process_content(content)\n```\n\nIn this example, `process_content()` is a hypothetical function that processes the content of the file in a safe way. You should replace it with the actual logic of your program.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses built-in Python functions.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
