            {
              "id": "71a01508-125d-3e3e-ae25-54f02f0f0ff3",
              "name": "Shell=True Subprocess Call Security Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `shell=True` option in Python's subprocess call is a security vulnerability. It allows for shell injection attacks, where an attacker can execute arbitrary commands on the system where the Python script is running. This is because when `shell=True` is used, Python uses the shell to execute the command, which means that shell syntax and shell special characters can be used. If any part of the command string that is passed to `subprocess.call()` comes from an untrusted source (like user input), then an attacker can use shell special characters to modify the command that is executed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using `shell=True` in subprocess calls whenever possible. If you need to use shell features, consider using the `shlex` library to safely create and manipulate shell commands. Always validate and sanitize input that is used in subprocess calls.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```python\nimport subprocess\ncommand = \"ls -l\"\nsubprocess.call(command, shell=True)\n```\n\nYou should use:\n\n```python\nimport subprocess\ncommand = [\"ls\", \"-l\"]\nsubprocess.call(command)\n```\n\nIn this example, the command is passed as a list of strings, which means that each string is treated as a separate argument and shell special characters in the strings do not have any special meaning.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `subprocess` library, which is included in the standard Python library and does not need to be installed separately.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Python Security - Command Injection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/OS_Command_Injection_Defense_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7a6efe89-13c4-3394-856c-ef96e17da5a5",
              "name": "Exec Usage Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Exec Usage Detected\" is a vulnerability in Python programming language that arises when the `exec()` function is used. The `exec()` function is a built-in Python function that executes the Python code contained within a string or object. If the input to the `exec()` function is not properly sanitized, it can lead to arbitrary code execution, which is a serious security risk.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `exec(f.read(), _globals)`, the `exec()` function is reading from a file and executing the contents. If an attacker can control the contents of this file, they can execute arbitrary Python code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using the `exec()` function whenever possible. If you must use it, ensure that the input is properly sanitized and that the executed code is not under the control of an attacker.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `exec()`, consider using safer alternatives that do not execute code, such as `eval()`. However, `eval()` also has its own security risks and should be used with caution. Always sanitize and validate input before using it in functions like `exec()` or `eval()`.\n\nHere is an example of how you might modify the provided code snippet:\n\n```python\n# Instead of this:\n# exec(f.read(), _globals)\n\n# Do this:\n_globals = {}\nwith open('filename', 'r') as f:\n    code = f.read()\n    sanitized_code = sanitize(code)  # Implement this function\n    if is_valid(sanitized_code):  # Implement this function\n        exec(sanitized_code, _globals)\n```\n\nIn this example, `sanitize()` and `is_valid()` are placeholder functions that you would need to implement. These functions should thoroughly sanitize and validate the code before it is executed.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
