            {
              "id": "86514621-ef8d-30cc-9aae-7c7098da59d3",
              "name": "Potential Interface Binding Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nPotential Interface Binding Vulnerability in Python refers to a situation where an application binds to a network interface that is accessible to untrusted networks. This can expose the application to attacks from untrusted networks. In the provided code snippet, the application is binding to a host that is fetched from an environment variable. If this environment variable is not properly controlled, it could lead to the application binding to an untrusted network interface.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n- Always bind to a trusted network interface. If the network interface is fetched from an environment variable, ensure that the environment variable is not accessible to an attacker.\n- Validate the host value before binding to it. This can prevent the application from binding to an untrusted network interface.\n- Use firewall rules to restrict access to the network interface. This can prevent an attacker from accessing the application through the network interface.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```python\nimport os\nimport socket\n\n# Get the host from the environment variable\nhost = os.environ.get(\"SANIC_HOST\", \"0.0.0.0\")\n\n# Validate the host\ntry:\n    socket.gethostbyname(host)\nexcept socket.gaierror:\n    # If the host is not valid, bind to a default trusted host\n    host = \"0.0.0.0\"\n\n# Continue with the rest of the code\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- os\n- socket\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-284: Improper Access Control](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
