            {
              "id": "d73311e8-6c99-38c7-b30a-4d144125777e",
              "name": "'Subprocess' Function 'check_output' with 'shell=True' Vulnerability Detected, Suggest Using 'shell=False'",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `subprocess` module in Python allows you to spawn new processes, connect to their input/output/error pipes, and obtain their return codes. The `check_output` function runs a command with arguments and returns its output. If `shell=True` is used in the `check_output` function, it can lead to shell injection vulnerabilities if the command string is constructed using unsanitized user input. This is because when `shell=True`, the specified command is executed through the shell, which has a number of features such as filename wildcarding, piping, here documents, command substitution, etc.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using `shell=True` with the `check_output` function, especially when the command string includes user input. Instead, use `shell=False` and provide the command and its arguments as a list. This way, the command is executed directly and does not go through the shell, thus avoiding shell injection vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```python\nimport subprocess\ncommand = \"ls -l\"  # This could be any command\noutput = subprocess.check_output(command, shell=True)\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```python\nimport subprocess\ncommand = [\"ls\", \"-l\"]  # This could be any command\noutput = subprocess.check_output(command, shell=False)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example only requires the built-in `subprocess` module in Python, so no additional library dependencies are needed.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d8d9824b-2a7b-32e6-bd48-634e6638a99b",
              "name": "Arbitrary Code Execution Vulnerability in `importlib.import_module()` Function Due to Untrusted User Input",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `importlib.import_module()` function in Python is used to programmatically import a module. If the `name` parameter of this function is controlled by an untrusted user input, it can lead to an Arbitrary Code Execution vulnerability. This is because an attacker can specify a module that contains malicious code, which will then be executed when the module is imported.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input to determine the module to be imported. If this is not possible, then the user input should be strictly validated to ensure that it only contains expected values. Additionally, it is recommended to use a safe method for importing modules, such as using a whitelist of allowed modules.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using user input to import a module, you can use a whitelist of allowed modules. Here is an example:\n\n```python\nallowed_modules = ['module1', 'module2', 'module3']\n\nif name in allowed_modules:\n    module = importlib.import_module(name)\nelse:\n    raise ValueError(f'Invalid module name: {name}')\n```\n\nIn this example, only the modules 'module1', 'module2', and 'module3' can be imported. If the user tries to import any other module, a `ValueError` will be raised.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly. The `importlib` module is part of the Python Standard Library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/OWASP_Code_Review_Guide_v2.pdf)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-706",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/706.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-706"
                ]
              }
            }
